<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<subsection xml:id="frequentist" >
      <title>The frequentist view</title>
      <p>
        The first of the two major approaches to probability, and the more dominant one in statistics, is referred to as the <em>frequentist view</em>, 
        and it defines probability as a <em>long-run frequency</em>. Suppose we were to try flipping a fair coin, over and over again. By definition, 
        this is a coin that has <m>P(H) = 0.5</m>. What might we observe? One possibility is that the first 20 flips might look like this:
      </p>
      <console>
      <output><![CDATA[T,H,H,H,H,T,T,H,H,H,H,T,H,H,T,T,T,T,T,H]]></output>
      </console>
      <p>
        In this case 11 of these 20 coin flips (55%) came up heads. Now suppose that I'd been keeping a running tally of the number of heads (which I'll call <m>N_H</m>) that I've seen, 
        across the first <m>N</m> flips, and calculate the proportion of heads <m>N_H / N</m> every time. Here's what I'd get (I did literally flip coins to produce this!):
      </p>
      <table xml:id="table-probability-coinflips">
        <title>Coin flip simulation results</title>
        <tabular halign="center">
          <row header="yes" bottom="minor">
            <cell halign="left">number of flips</cell>
            <cell>number of heads</cell>
            <cell>proportion</cell>
          </row>
          <row>
            <cell halign="left">1</cell>
